    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "Each row of the heatmap is one time segment and each column is a frequency bin (spaced at $f_s / \\text{seg\\_len} = 4$ Hz). The bright diagonal stripe running from bottom-left to top-right shows the chirp's instantaneous frequency rising from 5 Hz to 60 Hz over the 1-second duration. Energy is concentrated in a narrow band at each time step, confirming that the STFT successfully localises the signal in both time and frequency.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## Summary\n\n- **Chirp signals** sweep across frequencies; their spectrum is broad\n- **AM signals** produce sideband peaks at $f_c \\pm f_m$\n- **Windowing** (e.g., Hann) reduces spectral leakage at the cost of resolution\n- **PSD** estimates power distribution across frequencies\n- **Square waves** have only odd harmonics; truncated Fourier series exhibit the Gibbs phenomenon (~9% overshoot)\n- **STFT/Spectrogram** reveals time-varying frequency content by windowed FFT segments",
      "metadata": {}
    }
  ]
}